OSI Model (Session, Presentation & Application Layer)


1. Session Layer (Layer 5)

Responsible for creating and maintaining connections between computers.

Establishes a session when a connection becomes active.

Session remains active as long as the connection is active.

Manages and controls communication between systems.

Responsible for closing the connection if it remains idle.

Ensures organized communication between sender and receiver.



2. Presentation Layer (Layer 6)

Standardization starts at this layer.

Ensures data is handled in a uniform format, regardless of different software systems.

Acts as a translator between systems.

Translates data to and from the Application Layer.

Allows communication between systems using different formats.

Handles data encryption and decryption.

Example: HTTPS encryption happens at this layer.



3. Application Layer (Layer 7)

Determines how users interact with data being sent or received.

Defines protocols and rules for user interaction.

Applications like email clients, web browsers, and file transfer software operate at this layer.

Provides a Graphical User Interface (GUI) for users.

GUI helps users interact with sent and received data.

DNS (Domain Name System) works at this layer.

DNS translates domain names into IP addresses.
